<TITLE> Taiwan's Chen sees independence in his lifetime </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WASHINGTON, May 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Taiwan President Chen Shui-bian said on Tuesday he believes the island can achieve official independence from China during his lifetime, though not likely before he leaves office next year. "Perhaps this won't materialize during my term, however I believe in my lifetime this is a possibility," Chen told the National Press Club in Washington during a video conference from Taipei. "I believe 23 million people on Taiwan, most of the majority of people, hope to see that," he said in response to a question about independence. The 56-year-old president of self-ruled Taiwan is due to leave office next year after two terms. Term limits prevent him from running again. China and Taiwan have been separated since 1949 and Beijing sees the island as a renegade province. The Communist-ruled mainland has demanded that Taiwan accept reunification and has threatened force to stop it from embracing independence. Beijing distrusts the independence-leaning Chen, who won presidential elections for the Democratic Progressive Party in 2000 and 2004, and fears he will accelerate his agenda before he leaves offi
